PRESS DIGEST - Sweden - June 6 . Following are some of the leading stories in the Swedish papers this morning . Reuters has not verified these stories and does not vouch for their accuracy . DAGENS NYHETER - Companies such as fashion retail chain Hennes & Mauritz are fleeing the new share tax by taking the company off the stock exchange ' s primary list . Taxation minister Thomas Ostros says he will not relieve companies of the new tax until state finances are in order . - Since 1993 the number of homeless women in Stockholm rose 41 percent , but this figure only includes those who have been in contact with social authorities . A new count which will be ready this summer will take others into account . - The evening newspaper Expressen is buying an evening newspaper in Swedish west coast city Gothenburg , called GT , for 100 million crowns . Thereby Marieberg , controlled by the Bonnier family , owns three of four of Sweden ' s evening newspapers . SVENSKA DAGBLADET - Stefan Persson , chief executive and main owner of Swedish fashion retailer Hennes & Mauritz , will avoid paying 100 million crowns in wealth tax when transferring Hennes & Mauritz shares from the Stockholm bourse ' s main A list to the smaller O list . If the shares had remained on the A list Persson ' s taxes would have exceeded his dividend income . - Swedes fly more and more with foreign traffic increasing the most , up 11 percent in the first four months of the year compared to the corresponding period last year mostly due to more charter flights . - Tabloid Expressen , held by Swedish media group Marieberg , bought Gothenborg tabloid Goteborgstidningen ( GT ) from the Hjorne family ' s newspaper company Stampen for 100 million crowns . DAGENS INDUSTRI - Shares in Swedish clothing retailer Hennes & Mauritz plummeted 10 percent after the company said it was transfering its shares from the Stockholm Stock Exchange ' s primary A list to the stockmarket ' s smaller O list . A new wealth tax forces Swedes with wealth exceeding 900 , 000 crowns to pay 1 . 5 percent tax on 100 percent of the value of shares listed on the A list , up from 75 percent , while shares on the O list remain exempt from tax . - Swedish truckmaker Scania plans to boost profitability and fight competition by cutting its purchasing costs by several hundred million crowns annually . - Swedish vehicle makers Saab Automobile AB and AB Volvo both gained market share in Britain last month . New Volvo registrations rose 39 percent compared to the same 1996 period while for Saab they increased 31 percent . - - Stockholm newsroom + 46 - 8 - 700 1017 
